Two weeks after we chatted in person at Brooklyn=E2=80=99s Metropolitan Det=
ention Center, earlier this month, Sam Bankman-Fried was handcuffed to the =
seat of a prison bus and began his long journey to what will likely be his =
home for the foreseeable future: the medium-security federal prison in Mend=
ota, California. In the corrections trade, these cross-country bus trips ar=
e known as =E2=80=9Cdiesel therapy.=E2=80=9D According to the Federal Burea=
u of Prisons, Sam is currently at FTC Oklahoma City, which is described as =
=E2=80=9Can administrative federal security transfer center.=E2=80=9D

With no lawyers to distract him and endless hours to fill, Sam will surely =
be reflecting on his upcoming appeal. During our May 7 interview ( https://=
puck.news/exclusive-prison-chat-with-sam-bankman-fried/?utm_campaign=3DDry+=
Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%285%2F29%2F24%29&utm_content=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBE=
RS+%285%2F8%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_=
term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ), Sam seemed less focused on the $8 billion that=
 he misappropriated from FTX than the idea that the company=E2=80=99s outsi=
de counsel, Sullivan & Cromwell, had wronged him=E2=80=94in particular, by =
setting up a meeting with the U.S. Attorney=E2=80=99s office in the Souther=
n District of New York on November 9, 2022, ostensibly to flag FTX=E2=80=99=
s balance sheet crisis but also, in his telling, to exculpate itself and to=
 throw him under the metaphorical prison bus. The next day, S&C advised Sam=
 to step down as C.E.O. and turn over the company to John J. Ray III, who h=
as a long and impressive history of recovering
assets from failed businesses. Ray=E2=80=99s first act as chief executive w=
as to have FTX file for bankruptcy, which catalyzed the unwinding of the co=
mpany and the legal ramifications for Sam and many on his team. On March 28=
, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison
for misappropriating billions of dollars of customer funds and defrauding h=
is investors, among other criminal acts.

Sam was already up shit creek, of course. On the previous day, Binance C.E.=
O Changpeng Zhao announced that he had decided against bailing out FTX, pos=
sibly after being horrified by the increasingly obvious financial crisis at=
 the company and the sense that he was better off letting FTX fail. As FTX =
customers were becoming frustrated in their efforts to withdraw assets from=
 the exchange, Zhao=E2=80=99s decision exponentially increased the likeliho=
od that FTX would be forced into a bankruptcy filing.

In Sam=E2=80=99s revisionist history, however, he could have stayed in his =
role as C.E.O. and somehow recovered the company from its liquidity crisis.=
 In his conversations with me, Sam claimed he=E2=80=99d already circled $4 =
billion of the necessary $8 billion, though he didn=E2=80=99t name any of t=
he potential investors. Perhaps the absurdity of this
alternate reality explains why S.B.F. has fixated on the Sullivan & Cromwel=
l subplot. That said, it is a fascinating subplot=E2=80=A6

The Meeting

Details of what allegedly transpired during the November 9 meeting are stil=
l coming to light. But a recent research paper by two law professors, Penn=
=E2=80=99s David Skeel and Temple=E2=80=99s Jonathan Lipson, has attempted =
to add some insights into the events that day.

According to the academics, Sullivan & Cromwell and Ryne Miller, a former S=
&C partner who was general counsel at FTX=E2=80=8C.US, may have distorted t=
he legal process by telling the U.S. Attorney for the Southern District of =
New York that they were concerned about =E2=80=9Cproblems reconciling entit=
lements and digital assets on the FTX=E2=80=8C.US exchange.=E2=80=9D The pr=
ofessors=E2=80=99 source was a filing in bankruptcy court by Andrew Dietder=
ich, an S&C partner and one of the lead attorneys representing the debtors.=
 Sam told me he believes that lawyers at the firm also used the
meeting to brief prosecutors on their theory about Sam=E2=80=99s malfeasanc=
e at FTX, in an effort to try to absolve the firm from allegations of wrong=
doing by getting ahead of the curve with prosecutors.

In their paper, Skeel and Lipson raise the question of whether S&C =E2=80=
=9Chad the authority to report their concerns=E2=80=9D and if S&C should ha=
ve reported Miller=E2=80=99s findings about FTX=E2=80=8C.US to Sam first. A=
ccording to the professors, during the meeting S&C lawyers also =E2=80=9Cen=
tered into an agreement=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94or caused FTX to enter into an agr=
eement=E2=80=94to =E2=80=9Cvoluntarily produce documents=E2=80=9D for the p=
rosecutors, including financial statements, general ledgers, and employee c=
ontact information. A few days after the bankruptcy filing, on November 15,=
 S&C provided the first batch of documents to SDNY. Skeel and Lipson noted =
that S&C did not copy Bankman-Fried on its transmittal letter.

The two professors take Sullivan & Cromwell to task for =E2=80=9Cundisclose=
d potential
conflicts of interest=E2=80=9D and say the firm may have =E2=80=9Ccast a tr=
oubling shadow over puzzling and costly decisions in the case.=E2=80=9D And=
, alas, S&C=E2=80=99s direct communications with S.B.F. can seem misleading=
=2E At 9:30 p.m. on November 9, hours a=
fter the SDNY meeting, Dietderich emai=
led Sam and Miller that the firm was =E2=80=9Chere to help =E2=80=A6 howeve=
r we can,=E2=80=9D but didn=E2=80=99t mention that S&C had just met with th=
e U.S. Attorney=E2=80=99s Office. In the email, Dietderich acknowledged tha=
t Sam was focused on =E2=80=9Crescue alternatives at this time=E2=80=9D=E2=
=80=94i.e., trying to raise $8 billion ASAP to plug the giant liquidity hol=
e at FTX=E2=80=94and that Dietderich and the firm were focused instead on =
=E2=80=9Cthe safety net=E2=80=9D alternatives, a reference to a possible ba=
nkruptcy filing, which he wanted Sam to approve =E2=80=9Cin case you need i=
t.=E2=80=9D

In his email, Dietderich said the firm had =E2=80=9Cthe process=E2=80=9D un=
derway, but wanted Sam=E2=80=99s help in taking other, immediate steps. Spe=
cifically, he wanted Sam to name
a point person at FTX=E2=80=8C.US to help S&C collect the information it ne=
eded to prepare the filing. Furthermore, he wanted Sam to hire both Alvarez=
 & Marsal, a forensic accounting firm, for =E2=80=9Ccase prep,=E2=80=9D and=
 an external communications firm to prepare messaging around a possible ban=
kruptcy. Dietderich also made the case for Ray, writing that =E2=80=9Cideal=
ly=E2=80=9D Sam would =E2=80=9Cappoint a [chief restructuring officer] to b=
e on stand-by as the manager of the company in a possible chapter 11. We re=
commend Sam stay as a director. The manager is there because of conflicts. =
We have considered candidates and suggest John Ray. Resume attached. The C.=
R.O. works by the hour and can be terminated anytime. We can set up so he d=
oes nothing before a decision to file if you prefer.=E2=80=9D

In their paper, Skeel and Lipson point to peculiarities in Dietderich=E2=80=
=99s email. For example, he was recommending Ray as FTX=E2=80=99s chief res=
tructuring officer, not its C.E.O. Dietderich wrote, too, that
Ray could be =E2=80=9Cterminated anytime=E2=80=9D by Sam. The next day, Sam=
 told me, he was persuaded to sign the infamous =E2=80=9COmnibus Corporate =
Authority,=E2=80=9D ceding his role as C.E.O. of FTX to Ray, at the urging =
of both Sullivan & Cromwell and Sam=E2=80=99s lawyers at Paul Weiss. In tes=
timony Sam planned to give before Congress on December 13, 2022, he told me=
, he was going to say that he had wanted to rescind the Ray appointment and=
 the Omnibus Corporate Authority, but neither was apparently possible, cont=
rary to Dietderich=E2=80=99s assurances. (Instead of appearing before Congr=
ess on December 13, Sam was arrested in the Bahamas at the request of U.S. =
authorities.)

In his report published last week, however, FTX examiner Robert J. Cleary f=
ound that S&C did nothing wrong. =E2=80=9CThere was no error in the Court=
=E2=80=99s decision concerning the Debtor=E2=80=99s retention of S&C,=E2=80=
=9D Cleary concluded. Without mentioning Skeel and Lipson by name, Cleary w=
rote that =E2=80=9Ccertain academics have argued
that S&C=E2=80=99s cooperation with prosecutors may have violated S&C=E2=80=
=99s duties to the Debtors, wasted estate assets, or misled Bankman-Frieds=
=E2=80=A6 Specifically, these scholars allege that, prior to the Petition D=
ate, S&C violated its duty of confidentiality, candor, and loyalty to its c=
lient by disclosing to prosecutors, without proper authorization from the F=
TX Group, that a crime had occurred at the company.=E2=80=9D But, Cleary co=
ntinued, he did not see any =E2=80=9Cemail or other document in which S&C e=
xpressly disclosed a crime to prosecutors or regulators prepetition.=E2=80=
=9D

He noted that S&C disclosed to the government that FTX=E2=80=8C.US =E2=80=
=9Chad discovered an anomaly on its balance sheet=E2=80=94that there were n=
ot enough assets to cover liabilities,=E2=80=9D and that those anomalies di=
d not =E2=80=9Camount to=E2=80=9D and were not the =E2=80=9Cresult of=E2=80=
=9D a crime. Rather, Cleary concluded, =E2=80=9C[T]he FTX Group=E2=80=99s d=
ecision, in consultation with S&C, to make a swift and decisive self-disclo=
sure concerning the
balance sheet anomaly is consistent with the prudent and common strategy fo=
r companies to promptly self-disclose corporate misconduct, and may have he=
lped preserve estate resources by enabling the company to earn cooperation =
