In a statement to me, the firm said it was pleased with Cleary=E2=80=99s fi=
ndings: =E2=80=9CSullivan & Cromwell remains confident in our pre-petition =
work for FTX and the commencement of the Chapter 11 cases, and we welcome t=
he Examiner=E2=80=99s findings to date rejecting various baseless allegatio=
ns about our work for FTX. If the Court concludes that any points require f=
urther review, we will continue to cooperate fully with the Examiner.=E2=80=
=9D

The Wait

In a joint response, Skeel and Lipson conceded they might not have been ful=
ly informed about everything that transpired. For instance, they note that =
SDNY may already have been investigating Sam before November 9, and therefo=
re S&C=E2=80=99s meeting with the U.S. attorney=E2=80=99s office that day =
=E2=80=9Cmay have done little damage=E2=80=9D to Sam and indeed, =E2=80=9Cm=
ay have helped to prevent greater harm to the company.=E2=80=9D They questi=
oned why Sam=E2=80=99s attorneys at Paul Weiss didn=E2=80=99t do more to wa=
rn him about the repercussions of the Omnibus Corporate Authority document =
and how the appointment of Ray would change things for him dramatically. Bu=
t, they also note, there is =E2=80=9Cno evidence=E2=80=9D that Paul Weiss, =
or Sam, knew that S&C had =E2=80=9Cgone to prosecutors=E2=80=9D before Sam =
relinquished control of FTX to Ray in the early morning hours of November 1=
1. But he did it all the
same.

Overall, Lipson and Skeel described Cleary=E2=80=99s report as a mixed bag.=
 =E2=80=9CHe reports some important information that was not previously kno=
wn publicly, and he did so under difficult conditions,=E2=80=9D they explai=
ned. =E2=80=9CUnfortunately, he does not engage evidence that appears to be=
 critical=E2=80=94in particular the timing of S&C emails reassuring Bankman=
-Fried of his role at FTX without disclosing that the firm had gone to pros=
ecutors. He seems to rely heavily on the fact that Bankman-Fried had his ow=
n counsel, which has never been in dispute. The important question is: What=
 did those lawyers know about what S&C did, and when did they know it? If t=
here is an answer to that question in the Examiner=E2=80=99s Report, we hav=
e yet to see it.=E2=80=9D

The professors have a point. In any case, now that Cleary=E2=80=99s report =
has cleared S&C, we=E2=80=99ll likely have to wait until Sam=E2=80=99s appe=
al to see whether there is anything more to his theory that Sullivan & Crom=
well threw him under the
bus during its November 9 meeting. You can bet he=E2=80=99s thinking about =
it, and little else, during his diesel therapy.

