x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Two weeks after we =
chatted in person at Brooklyn=E2=80=99s Metropolitan Detention Center, earl=
ier this month, <b>Sam Bankman-Fried</b> was handcuffed to the seat of a pr=
ison bus and began his long journey to what will likely be his home for the=
 foreseeable future: the medium-security federal prison in Mendota, Califor=
nia. In the corrections trade, these cross-country bus trips are known as =
=E2=80=9Cdiesel therapy.=E2=80=9D According to the Federal Bureau of Prison=
s, Sam is currently at FTC Oklahoma City, which is described as =E2=80=9Can=
 administrative federal security transfer center.=E2=80=9D <br/> <br/>With =
no lawyers to distract him and endless hours to fill, Sam will surely be re=
flecting on his upcoming appeal. During our May 7 <u><a href=3D"https://ema=
il.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dQeHJCdUR4RFQzaE=
pWS1BkNnh2RT0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9wdWNrLm5ld3MvZXhjbHVzaXZlLXByaXNvbi1ja=
GF0LXdpdGgtc2FtLWJhbmttYW4tZnJpZWQvP3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1EcnkrUG93ZGVyKy0rU1VC=
U0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4NSUyRjI5JTJGMjQlMjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1fY29udGVudD1EcnkrUG93ZGVyKy0=
rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4NSUyRjglMkYyNCUyOVx1MDAyNnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWxfYWN0aW=
9uXHUwMDI2dXRtX3NvdXJjZT1jdXN0b21lci5pb1x1MDAyNnV0bV90ZXJtPWY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0M=
mFiZDEyYSIsImludGVybmFsIjoiZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwibGlua19pZCI6ODczNjQz=
fQ/2b2413453474ea1457705579192741fc37a8b0436392a9b78cb04127df334b63" style=
=3D"color:#d40000;text-decoration:none;font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">inte=
rview</a></u>, Sam seemed less focused on the $8 billion that he misappropr=
iated from FTX than the idea that the company=E2=80=99s outside counsel, Su=
llivan &amp; Cromwell, had wronged him=E2=80=94in particular, by setting up=
 a meeting with the U.S. Attorney=E2=80=99s office in the Southern District=
 of New York on November 9, 2022, ostensibly to flag FTX=E2=80=99s balance =
sheet crisis but also, in his telling, to exculpate itself and to throw him=
 under the metaphorical prison bus. The next day, S&amp;C advised Sam to st=
ep down as C.E.O. and turn over the company to <b>John J. Ray III</b>, who =
has a long and impressive history of recovering assets from failed business=
es. Ray=E2=80=99s first act as chief executive was to have FTX file for ban=
kruptcy, which catalyzed the unwinding of the company and the legal ramific=
ations for Sam and many on his team. On March 28, he was sentenced to 25 ye=
ars in prison
for misappropriating billions of dollars of customer funds and defrauding h=
is investors, among other criminal acts.<br/><br/>Sam was already up shit c=
reek, of course. On the previous day, Binance C.E.O <b>Changpeng Zhao</b> a=
nnounced that he had decided <i>against</i> bailing out FTX, possibly after=
 being horrified by the increasingly obvious financial crisis at the compan=
y and the sense that he was better off letting FTX fail. As FTX customers w=
ere becoming frustrated in their efforts to withdraw assets from the exchan=
ge, Zhao=E2=80=99s decision exponentially increased the likelihood that FTX=
 would be forced into a bankruptcy filing.<br/><br/>In Sam=E2=80=99s revisi=
onist history, however, he could have stayed in his role as C.E.O. and some=
how recovered the company from its liquidity crisis. In his conversations w=
ith me, Sam claimed he=E2=80=99d already <i>circled</i> $4 billion of the n=
ecessary $8 billion, though he didn=E2=80=99t name any of the potential inv=
estors. Perhaps the absurdity of this
alternate reality explains why S.B.F. has fixated on the Sullivan &amp; Cro=
mwell subplot. That said, it <i>is</i> a fascinating subplot=E2=80=A6<br/><=
/td>
