          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Details of what all=
egedly transpired during the November 9 meeting are still coming to light. =
But a recent research paper by two law professors, Penn=E2=80=99s <b>David =
Skeel</b> and Temple=E2=80=99s <b>Jonathan Lipson</b>, has attempted to add=
 some insights into the events that day. <br/><br/>According to the academi=
cs, Sullivan &amp; Cromwell and <b>Ryne Miller</b>, a former S&amp;C partne=
r who was general counsel at FTX=E2=80=8C.US, may have distorted the legal =
process by telling the U.S. Attorney for the Southern District of New York =
that they were concerned about =E2=80=9Cproblems reconciling entitlements a=
nd digital assets on the FTX=E2=80=8C.US exchange.=E2=80=9D The professors=
=E2=80=99 source was a filing in bankruptcy court by <b>Andrew Dietderich</=
b>, an S&amp;C partner and one of the lead attorneys representing the debto=
rs. Sam told me he believes that lawyers at the firm also used the
meeting to brief prosecutors on their theory about Sam=E2=80=99s malfeasanc=
e at FTX, in an effort to try to absolve the firm from allegations of wrong=
doing by getting ahead of the curve with prosecutors. <br/><br/>In their pa=
per, Skeel and Lipson raise the question of whether S&amp;C =E2=80=9Chad th=
e authority to report their concerns=E2=80=9D and if S&amp;C should have re=
ported Miller=E2=80=99s findings about FTX=E2=80=8C.US to Sam <i>first</i>.=
 According to the professors, during the meeting S&amp;C lawyers also =E2=
=80=9Centered into an agreement=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94or caused FTX to enter int=
o an agreement=E2=80=94to =E2=80=9Cvoluntarily produce documents=E2=80=9D f=
or the prosecutors, including financial statements, general ledgers, and em=
ployee contact information. A few days after the bankruptcy filing, on Nove=
mber 15, S&amp;C provided the first batch of documents to SDNY. Skeel and L=
ipson noted that S&amp;C did not copy Bankman-Fried on its transmittal lett=
er. <br/><br/>The two professors take Sullivan &amp; Cromwell to task for =
=E2=80=9Cundisclosed potential
conflicts of interest=E2=80=9D and say the firm may have =E2=80=9Ccast a tr=
oubling shadow over puzzling and costly decisions in the case.=E2=80=9D And=
, alas, S&amp;C=E2=80=99s direct communications with S.B.F. can seem mislea=
ding. At 9:30 p.m. on November 9, hours <i>after</i> the SDNY meeting, Diet=
derich emailed Sam and Miller that the firm was =E2=80=9Chere to help =E2=
=80=A6 however we can,=E2=80=9D but didn=E2=80=99t mention that S&amp;C had=
 just met with the U.S. Attorney=E2=80=99s Office. In the email, Dietderich=
 acknowledged that Sam was focused on =E2=80=9Crescue alternatives at this =
time=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94i.e., trying to raise $8 billion ASAP to plug the gia=
nt liquidity hole at FTX=E2=80=94and that Dietderich and the firm were focu=
sed instead on =E2=80=9Cthe safety net=E2=80=9D alternatives, a reference t=
o a possible bankruptcy filing, which he wanted Sam to approve =E2=80=9Cin =
case you need it.=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>In his email, Dietderich said the firm=
 had =E2=80=9Cthe process=E2=80=9D underway, but wanted Sam=E2=80=99s help =
in taking other, immediate steps. Specifically, he wanted Sam to name
a point person at FTX=E2=80=8C.US to help S&amp;C collect the information i=
t needed to prepare the filing. Furthermore, he wanted Sam to hire both Alv=
arez &amp; Marsal, a forensic accounting firm, for =E2=80=9Ccase prep,=E2=
=80=9D and an external communications firm to prepare messaging around a po=
ssible bankruptcy. Dietderich also made the case for Ray, writing that =E2=
=80=9Cideally=E2=80=9D Sam would =E2=80=9Cappoint a [chief restructuring of=
ficer] to be on stand-by as the manager of the company in a possible chapte=
r 11. We recommend Sam stay as a director. The manager is there because of =
conflicts. We have considered candidates and suggest John Ray. Resume attac=
hed. The C.R.O. works by the hour and can be terminated anytime. We can set=
 up so he does nothing before a decision to file if you prefer.=E2=80=9D<br=
/><br/>In their paper, Skeel and Lipson point to peculiarities in Dietderic=
h=E2=80=99s email. For example, he was recommending Ray as FTX=E2=80=99s ch=
ief <i>restructuring</i> officer, not its C.E.O. Dietderich wrote, too, tha=
t
Ray could be =E2=80=9Cterminated anytime=E2=80=9D by Sam. The next day, Sam=
 told me, he was persuaded to sign the infamous =E2=80=9COmnibus Corporate =
Authority,=E2=80=9D ceding his role as C.E.O. of FTX to Ray, at the urging =
of both Sullivan &amp; Cromwell and Sam=E2=80=99s lawyers at Paul Weiss. In=
 testimony Sam planned to give before Congress on December 13, 2022, he tol=
d me, he was going to say that he had wanted to rescind the Ray appointment=
 and the Omnibus Corporate Authority, but neither was apparently possible, =
contrary to Dietderich=E2=80=99s assurances. (Instead of appearing before C=
ongress on December 13, Sam was arrested in the Bahamas at the request of U=
=2ES. authorities.) <br/><br/>In his re=
port published last week, however, FTX=
 examiner<b> Robert J. Cleary</b> found that S&amp;C did nothing wrong. =E2=
=80=9CThere was no error in the Court=E2=80=99s decision concerning the Deb=
tor=E2=80=99s retention of S&amp;C,=E2=80=9D Cleary concluded. Without ment=
ioning Skeel and Lipson by name, Cleary wrote that =E2=80=9Ccertain academi=
cs have argued
that S&amp;C=E2=80=99s cooperation with prosecutors may have violated S&amp=
;C=E2=80=99s duties to the Debtors, wasted estate assets, or misled Bankman=
-Frieds=E2=80=A6 Specifically, these scholars allege that, prior to the Pet=
ition Date, S&amp;C violated its duty of confidentiality, candor, and loyal=
ty to its client by disclosing to prosecutors, without proper authorization=
 from the FTX Group, that a crime had occurred at the company.=E2=80=9D But=
, Cleary continued, he did not see any =E2=80=9Cemail or other document in =
which S&amp;C expressly disclosed a crime to prosecutors or regulators prep=
etition.=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>He noted that S&amp;C disclosed to the governme=
nt that FTX=E2=80=8C.US =E2=80=9Chad discovered an anomaly on its balance s=
heet=E2=80=94that there were not enough assets to cover liabilities,=E2=80=
=9D and that those anomalies did not =E2=80=9Camount to=E2=80=9D and were n=
ot the =E2=80=9Cresult of=E2=80=9D a crime. Rather, Cleary concluded, =E2=
=80=9C[T]he FTX Group=E2=80=99s decision, in consultation with S&amp;C, to =
make a swift and decisive self-disclosure concerning the
balance sheet anomaly is consistent with the prudent and common strategy fo=
r companies to promptly self-disclose corporate misconduct, and may have he=
lped preserve estate resources by enabling the company to earn cooperation =
credit.=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>In a statement to me, the firm said it was pleas=
ed with Cleary=E2=80=99s findings: =E2=80=9CSullivan &amp; Cromwell remains=
 confident in our pre-petition work for FTX and the commencement of the Cha=
pter 11 cases, and we welcome the Examiner=E2=80=99s findings to date rejec=
ting various baseless allegations about our work for FTX. If the Court conc=
ludes that any points require further review, we will continue to cooperate=
 fully with the Examiner.=E2=80=9D<br/></td>
